org.jgrapht.util

Class DoublyLinkedList<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jgrapht.util.DoublyLinkedList<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the list element type
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<E>

    public class DoublyLinkedList<E>
extends Object
implements Iterable<E>
    This is the implementation of the doubly linked list data structure, which gives access to the internal list nodes the data is stored in. The primary goal of this is to be able to delete an element from this list in $\mathcal{O}(1)$ via the list node it is stored in.

    The iterators over this list have a fail-fast behaviour meaning that they throw a ConcurrentModificationException after they detect a structural modification of the list, that they're not responsible for.

    Author:
    Timofey Chudakov

      • reverseIteratorFrom

        public Iterator<E> reverseIteratorFrom(E element)
        Returns an iterator over this list, which traverses the list in the reverse direction. The returned iterator will iterate over the entire list, that is, the list is treated as if it were cyclic. The iterator starts from element, and walks the list backwards, while wrapping around at the beginning of the list. For instance, for the list [1,2,3,4], reverseIteratorFrom(3) would return 3,2,1,4. This method throws NoSuchElementException in the case element doesn't belong to this list. This method invokes getNode to find the list node containing element.
        Parameters:
        element - an element to start an iteration from
        Returns:
        an iterator over this list, which starts from the element

      • invert

        public void invert()
        Inverts the list. For instance, calling this method on the list $(a,b,c,\dots,x,y,z)$ will result in the list $(z,y,x,\dots,c,b,a)$. This method does only pointer manipulation, meaning that all the list nodes allocated for the previously added elements are valid after this method finishes.

      • getNode

        public DoublyLinkedList.ListNode<E> getNode(E element)
        Finds and returns the list node allocate for the element. If this list doesn't contain the element, returns null. The time complexity of this method is linear in the size of the list under the assumption that the element comparison is done in constant time. Otherwise, the complexity is $\mathcal{O}(n\cdot h)$, where $n$ is the size of the list and $h$ is the time needed to compare two elements stored in this list.
        Parameters:
        element - the element of this list to search the list node of.
        Returns:
        the list node allocate for the element, or null if this list doesn't contain the element
